WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.240 --> 00:00:04.080
I wonder if people drive by.

00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:05.550
By and they're like, oh
my God, it's Melinda.

00:00:05.670 --> 00:00:06.150
No.

00:00:06.150 --> 00:00:07.080
I think they just drive and go.

00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:07.980
What's going on?

00:00:08.130 --> 00:00:11.340
Melinda French Gates is
opening up like never before.

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:13.770
Your book is about transitions,
about turning points.

00:00:13.770 --> 00:00:17.400
Do you feel like you've gone through
it now that you've crossed the chasm?

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:21.390
I feel like I'm still in transition. I
mean, I really am, and quite frankly,

00:00:21.390 --> 00:00:25.920
I hope my whole life I embrace change.
A billionaire, philanthropist, and.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:26.490
Investor.

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:28.770
Please welcome back to
the Late Show, Melinda.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:33.300
French Gates. Melinda's been a champion
for gender equality, education,

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:35.280
health and human rights around the globe.

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:37.890
Whether it's health, whether
it's decision-making,

00:00:37.890 --> 00:00:39.570
whether it's economic opportunity,

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:43.290
we won't get there as a world if we don't
make the right investments in women.

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:46.680
I've always believed that
to whom much is given,

00:00:47.100 --> 00:00:48.360
much is expected.

00:00:48.510 --> 00:00:50.820
Melinda is one of the
world's most powerful women,

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:54.180
but she's learned that no amount of
money or power protects you from the

00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:57.900
unexpected twists and turns of
life. Since the mid nineties,

00:00:57.900 --> 00:01:01.080
she's been known as a driving force of
the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation,

00:01:01.290 --> 00:01:05.070
often defined by her marriage to
the man behind the Microsoft empire,

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:07.920
but now she's stepping
into a new spotlight,

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:12.300
carving a path that's unmistakably
and unapologetically her own.

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:15.930
I wanted to get a sense of the
Melinda behind the headlines,

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:19.890
the Melinda before the Gates and travel
with her to a special place in Seattle

00:01:19.890 --> 00:01:21.570
where it all began.

00:01:21.570 --> 00:01:24.870
When she was just Melinda French
starting a new job at this little

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:26.250
company called Microsoft.

00:01:34.230 --> 00:01:37.560
This is the neighborhood where you
bought your first house. It is.

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:40.950
Does this bring back memories?
It does. It definitely does.

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:43.560
I loved living over here
on this side of the lake.

00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:46.380
And you bought this house with
your own money from Microsoft.

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:47.220
Stock. Absolutely.

00:01:47.310 --> 00:01:50.160
Which I'm guessing was a big
deal for a single gal back then.

00:01:50.250 --> 00:01:54.180
It was, it felt very independent
to do it, and I was so excited.

00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:57.210
Very grown up. What did Catholic
school girl, Melinda, from Dallas,

00:01:57.210 --> 00:02:00.450
think about you just striking
out on your own in Seattle?

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:02.880
I was exhilarated by the whole thing.

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:08.040
Your dad was part of the Apollo missions.
He told you to learn how to code.

00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:11.070
What was it about the tech
industry that hooked you?

00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:13.230
Well, I always loved math.

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:17.850
I was a math nerd coming out of
seventh and eighth grade and my female

00:02:17.850 --> 00:02:19.770
math teacher in high school,

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:23.610
she brought these computers into
the school about five Apple Twos,

00:02:24.210 --> 00:02:27.690
and it was just kind of the
adventure programming was like,

00:02:27.690 --> 00:02:28.830
it was both creative,

00:02:28.830 --> 00:02:33.420
but it was a logic problem and I like
logic problems. My dad bought us a

00:02:33.420 --> 00:02:36.780
computer at home, and so we
were not only programming,

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:40.710
but we were also keeping the books for
my parents for the real estate business,

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:42.690
so I also learned the flows of money.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:46.650
After graduating as high school
valedictorian, she went on to Duke,

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:49.710
earning both a BA in
computer science and an MBA.

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:55.560
In 1987, Melinda moved to
Seattle to join Microsoft.

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:59.830
The company was pioneering the software
revolution. It had just gone public,

00:02:59.980 --> 00:03:04.630
was releasing groundbreaking systems
like Windows 2.0 and Excel and Melinda

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:08.050
began rising through the ranks. What
was the culture of Microsoft back then?

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:10.870
For better or for worse, I want to know.

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:16.120
There were some odd characters including
one developer who drummed his way

00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:19.600
with drumsticks around his
office, and I thought, well,

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:23.920
there were some odd characters in
computer science at Duke and that's okay.

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:24.280
Yeah,

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:29.140
there weren't very many women and in
particular there weren't that many

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:32.140
technical women. It was
like a boys debate club.

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:35.680
You'd go into the meetings and you had
to have your points and know what you

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.070
were going to say and be ready
on your toes and think fast,

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:42.010
and I learned to play that game,

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:44.920
but it could be wearing over time.

00:03:45.430 --> 00:03:47.650
You met Bill shortly after
you joined Microsoft?

00:03:47.650 --> 00:03:48.310
I did.

00:03:48.310 --> 00:03:52.810
Did you have any idea how dramatically
your life was about to change?

00:03:53.890 --> 00:03:55.120
No. No, no, no.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:59.410
Because I was dating him and I was
dating a few other people and I had a

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:02.980
large group of friends outside
of work and with those friends,

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:06.880
I would go off to coffee
houses or we'd go to films.

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:09.430
We would go hiking on the Olympic
Peninsula on the weekends.

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:13.780
I didn't know that things over
time we'd become serious with Bill.

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:17.800
When did you realize, oh my gosh, my
life is never going to be the same?

00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:21.760
We dated quite a lot. We'd
broken up a few times,

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:25.630
but I do know on the day
I got engaged, I was like,

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.180
whoa, what have I bitten off here?

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.960
Melinda went from the anonymity of being
an independent career woman to a life

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:38.560
in the spotlight, married to the
world's most famous tech scion.

00:04:39.130 --> 00:04:43.750
She stayed on at Microsoft through the
iconic Windows 95 launch and had a hand

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:47.710
in a little known project that was,
let's just say ahead of its time.

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:52.870
When you worked at Microsoft, you had
this project called Microsoft Bob. Yes,

00:04:52.870 --> 00:04:54.940
A complete failure. I mean,

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:59.740
some of those early concepts in Bob
are actually starting to come to

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:00.490
fruition now.

00:05:00.490 --> 00:05:05.020
So the thing that people always like
to make fun of is Clippy Clippy. Yes.

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:07.030
Oh yes. Oh, you remember Clippy? Yes.

00:05:07.030 --> 00:05:11.770
Clippy actually was one of the early
agents that came up in publisher and

00:05:12.070 --> 00:05:13.060
then Bob.

00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:17.380
The idea of an agent was really there.

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:19.270
In spite of its failure, today,

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:22.690
Bob is seen as a prelude to
AI assistance like ChatGPT.

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:27.010
Belinda also played a part in some of
Microsoft's greatest early successes like

00:05:27.010 --> 00:05:30.460
Word and Expedia. But two years
after her marriage to Bill,

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:34.600
Melinda left the company to focus on
raising their children. Daughter Jennifer,

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:37.750
followed by son Rory and
their youngest Phoebe.

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:40.000
What did you do to try
to keep things normal?

00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:45.010
I made sure my kids went to the local
schools here they have to deal with which

00:05:45.010 --> 00:05:47.680
kids are sincere, which
kids aren't sincere,

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.170
who puts on a show because it's my kids.

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:54.820
I went through the years of navigating
the flip phone and later the smartphone

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:59.150
and working with other parents or if
there were disciplinary problems or if my

00:05:59.150 --> 00:06:00.230
kids got in trouble,

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:05.330
so I just tried to keep life
for them as normal as we could.

00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:09.230
What was never normal? Never normal.

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:14.840
Having a trampoline room inside your
house. I've actually been in there.

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:17.090
That's a pretty cool
room. Phoebe, my youngest,

00:06:17.090 --> 00:06:20.810
her big thing was she used to try to get
any adult she could get at a cocktail

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:22.400
party to go on the trampoline.

00:06:23.810 --> 00:06:26.510
You had this power career
risen up in management.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:31.400
What was the transition like to
leave work and be a mom full-time and

00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:32.270
let that go?

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:32.960
Really,

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:37.400
that had a lot to do with Bill was the
CEO and traveling all over the world and

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:41.900
to have the family life we wanted to
have. I felt like I wanted to be home,

00:06:42.260 --> 00:06:46.910
but it was really hard on me,
so much harder than I expected.

00:06:47.210 --> 00:06:50.000
I have this new little
baby who I adore and love,

00:06:50.600 --> 00:06:52.310
but I don't have my career anymore.

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:56.210
I'm not around all these hard
charging people, intellectual topics.

00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:59.540
So much of the world defined
you not based on who you are,

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:00.920
but who you were married to.

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:05.780
Did the pressure on Bill or
Microsoft and you ever make you feel

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:07.460
alone or stuck?

00:07:10.910 --> 00:07:14.060
Well, I didn't define
myself that way. Good,

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:18.170
so I knew how I was all along, so I think

00:07:20.030 --> 00:07:22.220
there were times I felt pressure,

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:26.060
but I could turn to my friends and
they would remind me, no, no, no, no,

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:28.430
you got this. You're smart
enough to figure this out.

00:07:28.430 --> 00:07:32.900
So I had to learn over time
how to rebuild that for myself

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:37.040
through my friendships and also start
doing some board work so I could stay

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:37.873
engaged.

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:42.770
She did more than just stay engaged.
Melinda helped revolutionize philanthropy.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.510
She took the reins of their foundation
with plans to put billions of dollars

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:48.380
back into the world.

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:52.820
They began funding solutions to some of
the world's most pressing problems like

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:56.240
education, vaccines,
maternal and child health.

00:07:56.930 --> 00:07:57.980
In 2010,

00:07:58.040 --> 00:08:01.610
the couple joined forces with Warren
Buffett to create the Giving Pledge.

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:03.680
You're seeing more and
more people come forward.

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:07.580
We have 40 other couples signed up in the
United States who have pledged to give

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:10.370
away over 50% of their
wealth. That's huge.

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:13.880
I don't believe in spending money that
doesn't do anything for me when it will

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:15.110
do something for somebody else.

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:19.400
Some people think it's inspiring, but
it's all talk. There's no accountability.

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:21.680
Are you tracking it and is it working?

00:08:22.190 --> 00:08:24.620
We are tracking it to the extent we can,

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:29.060
but what I do know is that a lot of the
philanthropists have learned from one

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:32.930
another and they'll get inspired by
another philanthropist and then get going.

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:34.460
For three decades,

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:37.160
Bill and Melinda Gates built their
empire of growing and giving,

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:39.860
but not without some damaging headlines.

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:43.370
There were reports of questionable
investments and programs,

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:46.280
Bill's association with Jeffrey Epstein,

00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:52.040
and allegations of marital infidelity.
What was it that made you ultimately say,

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:53.480
I need to get out of this marriage?

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:59.340
Yeah. The details about that will
remain between Bill and me and our kids.

00:09:00.270 --> 00:09:03.630
That was a very painful
time for all five of us,

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:06.690
and I think it deserves privacy.

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:09.750
As many people who've
gone through divorce note,

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:11.970
it's rarely one thing that happens.

00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:14.880
It's a series of things over time.

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:19.080
He said that the dissolution of
your marriage is his biggest regret.

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:21.540
What was your reaction to that?

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:26.220
It is sad that the behavior that
happened led to the dissolution of our

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:26.880
marriage.

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:31.740
It was the behavior and you
have to change your behavior to

00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:35.010
be able to be in a trusting,
intimate relationship,

00:09:35.010 --> 00:09:39.180
and if that can't happen over time
and you've given many chances,

00:09:39.180 --> 00:09:42.150
then there are consequences. Right.

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:45.750
What about you? Did you let go
of any dreams along the way?

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:47.760
Sure. The day I got married,

00:09:47.760 --> 00:09:51.270
I dreamt I was going to be married
for my whole life. That is not,

00:09:52.170 --> 00:09:54.870
that's not something you let go of easily.

00:09:54.870 --> 00:09:58.770
So I had to really think and
feel through that decision,

00:09:59.130 --> 00:10:03.750
but the thing that I knew and that some
people could hold out perspective for me

00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:06.870
is I was going to be
happier on the other side.

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:09.990
Initially, Melinda stayed
on at the foundation,

00:10:10.620 --> 00:10:14.070
but after finalizing the divorce decided
it was time to close that chapter

00:10:15.690 --> 00:10:18.390
too. A year later, Bill announced
that over the next 20 years,

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:20.940
the foundation will distribute
almost all of his wealth,

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:24.210
more than $200 billion and close up shop.

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:28.860
Melinda is continuing her
philanthropy on her own,

00:10:29.070 --> 00:10:32.190
putting 12 and a half billion dollars
to work through Pivotal Ventures,

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:34.350
her investment and advocacy organization.

00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:37.560
So this is my office.

00:10:37.680 --> 00:10:38.730
So tell me what we got going on here.

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:43.020
Just all kinds of things. A
woman gave me this in Malawi.

00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:46.530
I was just down in Louisiana
last week and it was Mardi Gras.

00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:48.720
We were actually learning
about maternal mortality. Gosh,

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.280
and the organization gave me these.

00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:54.510
So what do you need to feel
focused? Tell me about your routine.

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:55.920
Well,

00:10:55.920 --> 00:11:00.870
you might be surprised that I
definitely read email on my computer,

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:03.480
but I actually prefer to
have a lot of things printed.

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:05.310
I can focus more if it's printed.

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:06.540
Hang on. Sorry.

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:07.793
Boss lady.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:10.200
Boss lady.

00:11:10.500 --> 00:11:13.950
I love that. Okay, so my
daughter, Phoebe, my youngest,

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:19.440
one of her female girlfriends gave me
this senior year of high school when she

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:22.650
graduated high school. She's like,
you've been my mentor in life,

00:11:22.650 --> 00:11:26.490
and you're just like the ultimate boss
lady. I was like, is that a good thing?

00:11:26.490 --> 00:11:30.600
I hope so. You're making
all of these bets,

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:33.210
these gifts, doing all
this research on your own.

00:11:33.630 --> 00:11:38.550
What are you seeing that you can do
differently given your social capital and

00:11:38.550 --> 00:11:39.383
your economic power?

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:43.860
Well, I'm using every tool in my
toolbox, whether that's advocacy,

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:47.100
whether that's philanthropy,
whether that's investments,

00:11:47.190 --> 00:11:51.750
because I think all of those things
are needed if we're going to really

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:54.640
advance women to their
rightful place in society.

00:11:55.480 --> 00:11:58.780
Leaving the foundation was something that

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:02.470
weighed very heavily on me,

00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:06.790
but it became just clear to me that the US

00:12:07.360 --> 00:12:09.940
was changing very rapidly before our eyes,

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:14.710
that women's rights were being
rolled back and that I had a lot of

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:18.760
work ahead of me that I wanted to do
on that and to use my voice behind.

00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:21.670
I mean, you were high
school valedictorian.

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:24.580
You were the only woman in
your class at Microsoft.

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:26.920
You impressed one of the
smartest men in the world,

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:30.070
and yet you still at times
felt like an imposter.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:33.550
Is there something that you
say to yourself to psych
yourself up in the morning?

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:39.220
I want to say it with you because
so many super successful women

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:40.420
still feel that way.

00:12:41.350 --> 00:12:44.320
I think we have to look at the
root of why we feel that way.

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:49.870
Society is constantly telling
us otherwise in so many

00:12:49.870 --> 00:12:53.200
places. We walk in and
there's no one else like us,

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.820
or you don't see somebody who's
a role model ahead of you,

00:12:57.820 --> 00:13:01.390
or you are literally told
you don't belong here,

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:04.600
or you sit at a table and
people all talk over you.

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:09.370
So society gives us these messages
and we do have to push back on them.

00:13:09.370 --> 00:13:13.630
So when I have doubt, I
remind myself, don't be quiet.

00:13:13.930 --> 00:13:16.450
If I start to feel like
I want to be quiet,

00:13:16.450 --> 00:13:19.780
I have to think about what happened
that made me feel that way,

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:23.050
and remember that's often about
somebody else, not about me.

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:27.190
At Pivotal, she's centering on
the needs of women and girls,

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:31.360
committing $1 billion towards
advancing the power of women globally.

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:36.100
Women do things differently as we've
been discussing. Mackenzie Scott,

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:38.440
I'm curious what you think
of her style of giving.

00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:41.530
She's known for this more sort
of no strings attached approach,

00:13:41.590 --> 00:13:45.010
whereas the Gates Foundation
has historically been more
sort of data-driven and

00:13:45.010 --> 00:13:47.920
strategic. What do you think
of her style of giving?

00:13:48.010 --> 00:13:50.410
I think it's fantastic for her,

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:54.130
for where she is and what
she wants to accomplish.

00:13:54.130 --> 00:13:56.770
She is living her values out in society.

00:13:56.800 --> 00:13:59.440
She's not just giving to
any organization out there.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:04.300
She's giving to organizations that
she thinks are changing society and

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:07.810
who are effective, and I think
that's phenomenal. Good for her.

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:11.650
I wish more people would put
their money where their mouth is.

00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:15.070
I know you're friends with her. I'm
curious how she's influenced you.

00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:18.880
Did you reach out to her as you were
trying to figure out how to leave your

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:20.770
marriage and then the foundation?

00:14:21.460 --> 00:14:26.290
I would say probably the last eight
years we formed even more of a

00:14:26.290 --> 00:14:29.620
friendship. She's had a little more time
as some of her kids go off to college,

00:14:29.620 --> 00:14:30.453
so have I,

00:14:31.630 --> 00:14:35.560
and so we have just a really nice candid,

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:36.640
supportive friendship.

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:39.670
Women are actually coming
into a lot more money.

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:42.520
How could that change society?

00:14:42.970 --> 00:14:47.470
I think it will change
society fundamentally,

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:50.650
especially if women control the money
and can spend it the way they want.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:54.560
When a woman gets an extra
equivalent of a dollar in her hand,

00:14:54.950 --> 00:14:57.890
she spends it on her
children and on her family,

00:14:57.950 --> 00:15:00.680
and she spends it on
medications for her children.

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:04.340
So women make different
investments versus men.

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:07.310
I also think when women
control more resources,

00:15:07.490 --> 00:15:10.160
they will fund other women's businesses.

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:15.170
Is there a group power Women chat
with you and Mackenzie and Laurene and

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:16.003
Priscilla?

00:15:16.370 --> 00:15:20.900
Do you trade notes about
how to navigate this life?

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:23.840
Absolutely, but I've even
in the last two years,

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:28.670
especially after I saw what's happened
to women's rights in this country,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.150
I've reached out to friends of friends
that I never would've known before,

00:15:32.150 --> 00:15:36.620
even in Silicon Valley and have gone and
had a number of coffees and teas to try

00:15:36.620 --> 00:15:39.860
and get their perspective of what's
going on. Where are you investing?

00:15:39.860 --> 00:15:42.470
How are you thinking about our democracy?

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.660
Melinda's new endeavor coincides with
seismic changes in the US government.

00:15:48.530 --> 00:15:52.070
Her life's work is facing huge
setbacks under a new administration.

00:15:52.670 --> 00:15:54.920
Our golden age has just begun.

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:58.850
President yesterday talked about the
DOGE's strategy for cutting the federal

00:15:58.850 --> 00:15:59.840
workforce at large.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:02.870
The new Trump administration has all been
eliminated the world's leading global

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:06.650
aid agency and frozen spending or try
to on thousands of federal programs

00:16:06.650 --> 00:16:08.780
including vital scientific
and medical research.

00:16:09.350 --> 00:16:11.960
How is President Trump and these actions,

00:16:11.960 --> 00:16:14.000
how is this impacting
the philanthropic world?

00:16:14.180 --> 00:16:16.910
The cuts in USAID alone,

00:16:17.300 --> 00:16:21.950
16.9 million women will
not get maternal health

00:16:21.950 --> 00:16:22.783
services.

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:27.170
People are going hungry because
of those cuts as Americans.

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:28.280
Is that what we want?

00:16:28.340 --> 00:16:33.020
Do we want to create more crises around
the world or do we want peace and

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:35.900
prosperity for others so
they can live where they are?

00:16:35.930 --> 00:16:40.580
Philanthropy can take a risk that we
wouldn't want government to take with our

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:41.750
taxpayer funding,

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:46.820
but it can prove things out at scale
and then governments can come in

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:47.990
to scale that up.

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:52.340
Elon Musk and DOGE, how
do you feel about one man,

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:56.450
a billionaire having that much independent
power within the federal government?

00:16:57.110 --> 00:17:02.000
Well, it's unprecedented to
have anyone come in and say,

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:06.500
we're just going to wipe it out like
that. That makes no sense to me.

00:17:06.950 --> 00:17:10.850
President Trump handed more power
over to Elon Musk yesterday,

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:15.380
giving the billionaire and
his team oversight over
hiring decisions across every

00:17:15.380 --> 00:17:16.280
government agency.

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:21.080
We have never in American
history seen a lineup of business

00:17:21.080 --> 00:17:25.940
tycoons occupying a place of honor
at a presidential inauguration.

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:30.230
What do you make of the tech billionaires
lining up behind President Trump and

00:17:30.230 --> 00:17:31.700
Silicon Valley's right turn?

00:17:32.660 --> 00:17:37.580
What I have seen in the last six
to months to a year is many people

00:17:37.580 --> 00:17:42.080
who used to say one thing have
absolutely shifted over here, look,

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:46.790
a democracy is made up by our
beliefs and our investments

00:17:46.850 --> 00:17:48.470
and our values,

00:17:48.710 --> 00:17:52.380
and of all times right now should
be living those values out,

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:57.360
not pivoting to what some comms person
tells us is the right thing to do. Right?

00:17:57.360 --> 00:17:58.590
That would be ridiculous.

00:17:58.590 --> 00:18:02.070
The rollback of DEI, how's that going
to be written in the history books?

00:18:02.190 --> 00:18:05.730
Not favorably. Again, you
have to look at society.

00:18:06.390 --> 00:18:11.310
Who's in society right now and does our
democracy do our state legislatures and

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:15.240
does our Senate and does our
Congress look like society?

00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:16.980
And the answer is no.

00:18:17.130 --> 00:18:21.450
The reason you need to have all
of society represented in the

00:18:21.450 --> 00:18:26.430
legislature in any governing body
is because they make good policy

00:18:26.430 --> 00:18:29.070
based on their lived experience.

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:33.480
As DEI initiatives are slashed,
Melinda is trying to fill the gaps.

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:38.070
Pivotal has earmarked $150 million to
put towards equity and inclusion in the

00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:42.870
workplace, specifically the tech
industry. It's estimated that by 2030,

00:18:42.870 --> 00:18:45.660
86% of businesses will
be transformed by AI.

00:18:46.230 --> 00:18:49.530
As protections for women are
rolled back around the globe,

00:18:49.530 --> 00:18:53.220
Melinda wants to ensure their seat
at the table. The make men great

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:55.350
again movement. What's your take on that?

00:18:55.380 --> 00:18:59.850
I don't ever like anything that pits
women versus men or men versus women.

00:19:00.060 --> 00:19:00.960
That's not healthy for.

00:19:00.960 --> 00:19:01.793
Society.

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:06.510
There's a generation of boys coming up
that statistics show are less likely to

00:19:06.510 --> 00:19:09.840
go to college, are more
likely to feel alone,

00:19:10.170 --> 00:19:13.020
feel their opportunities
are slipping away.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:16.920
What do you think is going on
there and what can we do about it?

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:21.000
Well, I think we need to make
investments in those boys.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.840
They need more role models.
It can be a good coach,

00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:26.580
it can be a teacher at school,

00:19:26.610 --> 00:19:31.560
but we need to come together and really
deeply understand what's going on with

00:19:31.560 --> 00:19:33.900
our boys. There's been
some good research on this,

00:19:34.290 --> 00:19:36.780
but further I think needs to be done.

00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:41.520
The truth is there are many great men in
society and there are many great women

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:42.353
in society.

00:19:42.540 --> 00:19:47.460
We need to support both so that they
both get to where they want to be

00:19:47.460 --> 00:19:49.200
in society and can thrive.

00:19:49.380 --> 00:19:50.790
What advice are you giving your son?

00:19:51.750 --> 00:19:54.060
Keep going. Keep doing what you're doing.

00:19:54.060 --> 00:19:56.730
He has always believed in women's rights.

00:19:56.820 --> 00:20:01.440
He also helps keep me
educated, sending me articles.

00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:04.950
Have you considered this? Think
about this other point of view, mom,

00:20:04.950 --> 00:20:07.410
I know this is your point of view,
but think about this other one.

00:20:08.130 --> 00:20:12.480
You talk about not needing to be a
perfect parent, but a good enough parent.

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:13.650
Can you explain that?

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:18.300
It's a concept I didn't learn until my
kids were in middle school ages and I

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:20.130
wish I had learned earlier.

00:20:20.550 --> 00:20:25.140
I'd always been this perfectionist
and that's not always a good thing,

00:20:25.500 --> 00:20:27.000
especially as you're a mom.

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:31.950
And so when I finally learned this
concept of that children need one

00:20:32.250 --> 00:20:34.950
good enough parent and
they're going to be okay,

00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:39.690
I could let my guard down because there
is no such thing as a perfect parent.

00:20:39.750 --> 00:20:43.620
I thought why am certainly a
good enough parent? These kids,

00:20:43.620 --> 00:20:44.700
they're going to be okay.

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:47.620
I appreciate that you're
still speaking up about women.

00:20:47.890 --> 00:20:51.760
It does seem like the conversation
about women making strides has gone very

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:52.593
quiet.

00:20:53.110 --> 00:20:54.580
I don't think the voices are gone,

00:20:55.180 --> 00:21:00.130
but sometimes when you are
strategizing and you're figuring out

00:21:00.130 --> 00:21:01.180
where you go next,

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:06.280
geopolitically things have changed
massively in the last few months

00:21:06.310 --> 00:21:07.143
massively.

00:21:07.480 --> 00:21:12.400
So how we strategize and where
we make investments and where

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:15.940
we use our voices, just
give a little time.

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:18.760
I hope you're right. I hope you're right.

00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:21.610
The best answer is not
always the quickest answer.

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:26.590
So it's not always first mover or
first speaker that has the advantage.

00:21:26.590 --> 00:21:29.170
Sometimes it's the person
who quietly strategizes.

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:31.660
Melinda French Gates 3.0.

00:21:32.290 --> 00:21:35.530
What is the next chapter
that hasn't been written?

00:21:36.430 --> 00:21:39.670
Who knows? I am so excited.

00:21:40.180 --> 00:21:44.050
At least another decade of work
and then we'll see from there.

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:50.680
What's your take on where we're headed?

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:54.070
I don't think any of us know
where we're headed, quite frankly.

00:21:54.070 --> 00:21:58.540
We've never had an administration
quite like this one,

00:21:58.570 --> 00:22:02.680
and also some of the administrations
now around the world in Europe.

00:22:03.820 --> 00:22:08.020
So anybody who tells you they
know exactly where we are headed,

00:22:08.020 --> 00:22:08.740
I don't think we do.

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:10.660
Are you optimistic or worried?

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:15.070
I'm concerned is probably
the best way to say it.

00:22:15.460 --> 00:22:19.900
I am optimistic when I see
great work still going on in

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:22.090
communities and at the state level,

00:22:22.420 --> 00:22:27.040
but when you see certain directives
coming down and things happening so

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:27.873
swiftly,

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:32.470
that's deeply concerning to me
And especially the rollbacks for women.

00:22:32.470 --> 00:22:35.080
So for me, my work continues.

00:22:36.070 --> 00:22:40.150
I really want to make sure that women can
step into their full power and advance

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:42.130
in society in both the US and globally.

00:22:42.190 --> 00:22:46.870
I believe that we need to create a world
and make changes in the world where

00:22:46.870 --> 00:22:50.620
women can fully step into
their power. We all have power,

00:22:51.310 --> 00:22:54.400
but there are barriers in
society that hold women back.

00:22:54.820 --> 00:22:56.320
For a woman to have her full power,

00:22:56.320 --> 00:22:58.900
she needs to be able to voice
what she thinks is true,

00:22:59.200 --> 00:23:01.930
make her own decisions about
herself and her family,

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:05.830
and have her own resources that she
can decide where and how to spend them.

00:23:05.920 --> 00:23:09.700
So do you finally feel
unburdened by what has been?

00:23:10.030 --> 00:23:13.900
I feel very much that I can make the
decisions I want to make live the life I

00:23:13.900 --> 00:23:15.940
fully want to live and use the resources,

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:21.250
which I believe is to whom much
is given, much is expected,

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:25.270
and so anybody in society who is

00:23:25.510 --> 00:23:29.200
unbelievably privileged,
which I am, any of us,

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:33.430
owe the world to give that back and to
give that back thoughtfully for others.

00:23:48.830 --> 00:23:51.590
The country's also in
transition right now.

00:23:53.180 --> 00:23:56.060
Let's wait for the plane to
transition out of our sky.

